T1  - ON THE SOURCES OF UNCERTAINTY IN EXCHANGE RATE PREDICTABILITY
AU  - Byrne, Joseph P.
AU  - Korobilis, Dimitris
AU  - Ribeiro, Pinho J.
Y1  - 2018/02/01
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2018/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12271
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 329
EP  - 357
VL  - 59
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12271
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract In a unified framework, we examine four sources of uncertainty in exchange rate forecasting models: (i) random variations in the data, (ii) estimation uncertainty, (iii) uncertainty about the degree of time variation in coefficients, and (iv) uncertainty regarding the choice of the predictor. We find that models that embed a high degree of coefficient variability yield forecast improvements at horizons beyond one month. At the one-month horizon, and apart from the standard variance implied by unpredictable fluctuations in the data, the second and third sources of uncertainty listed above are key obstructions to predictive ability. The uncertainty regarding the choice of the predictors is negligible.
ER  - 

